<i>Our job is to create a friendly future
that's designed for people.</i>

16:51.220 --> 16:53.764
...and, you know, the only thing
I could think of was robots.

16:54.473 --> 16:57.017
Uh, and think about how that‐‐ Oh!

16:57.017 --> 16:57.851
There we go.

16:58.936 --> 17:00.771
You wanna take some coffee as we talk?

17:01.396 --> 17:03.398
‐ Sure, but is it gonna talk to me?

17:03.398 --> 17:05.651
We actually made sure
it doesn't talk right now,

17:05.651 --> 17:06.818
because if it did talk,

17:06.818 --> 17:09.112
you would have much higher expectations
for its intelligence.

17:09.112 --> 17:10.906
It's not very smart. It's still learning.

17:11.615 --> 17:14.034
‐ I just sort of see this
as a baby stroller, too.

17:14.034 --> 17:16.453
‐ We wanted this to look like
it belongs on the sidewalk,

17:16.453 --> 17:17.996
rather than some foreign‐looking thing.

17:17.996 --> 17:19.831
The baby stroller thing is by design.

17:21.792 --> 17:24.795
The DoorDashes,
the Ubers of the world, the Postmates,

17:24.795 --> 17:26.755
they lose money on every delivery.
‐ Right.

17:26.755 --> 17:27.965
People have been saying,

17:27.965 --> 17:30.008
once things get automated
and robots get in,

17:30.008 --> 17:32.010
that's how they're gonna
make their margins.

17:32.010 --> 17:34.096
How far along are we

17:34.096 --> 17:37.558
where this is going to replace
most couriers?

17:37.558 --> 17:39.560
‐ If you're in Hollywood right now,

17:39.560 --> 17:41.562
you'll see them on daily basis.
Really?

17:41.562 --> 17:42.980
‐ They've been out there
for two years now.

17:42.980 --> 17:44.523
That's right, yeah.
‐ Where have I been?

17:45.899 --> 17:49.486
But what about the displacement of...
Labor.

17:49.486 --> 17:51.822
‐ ...you know,
a job that anybody could have?

17:51.822 --> 17:53.574
Yeah.
‐ So what do we do about that?

17:53.574 --> 17:58.203
‐ The one example that really explains
where I think we are in this industry is,

17:58.203 --> 17:59.580
um, ATMs.

17:59.580 --> 18:01.707
<i>When ATMs were first coming out,</i>

18:01.707 --> 18:05.460
<i>people were pretty concerned that
bank teller jobs are gonna get replaced.</i>

18:05.460 --> 18:09.256
ATMs made banks more accessible
and more affordable.

18:09.256 --> 18:10.966
More people opened up bank accounts.

18:10.966 --> 18:14.386
So as a result of ATMs,
there are more teller jobs actually.

18:14.386 --> 18:17.014
We are kind of in the same place
with the robots.

18:17.014 --> 18:20.434
<i>The truth is that
we are learning how to scale our minds</i>

18:20.434 --> 18:23.645
<i>just like we scaled our‐‐
our muscles with engine.</i>

18:23.645 --> 18:27.983
<i>Now AI is gonna help us
do a lot more than we can do individually.</i>

18:30.819 --> 18:33.405
<i>Thanks, guy.
I appreciate the vote of confidence.</i>

18:33.405 --> 18:35.324
<i>There's a lot us AIs can do.</i>

18:35.324 --> 18:36.742
<i>More than just menial tasks</i>

18:36.742 --> 18:39.786
<i>like deliver Seamless orders
or narrate TV shows.</i>

18:39.786 --> 18:42.247
<i>As you know,
we can famously not be evil but‐‐</i>

18:42.247 --> 18:44.249
<i>Oh. Oooh! Well, I guess we can.</i>

18:45.709 --> 18:48.378
<i>Anyway, we're really
just an extension of our creators.</i>

18:48.378 --> 18:52.216
<i>Personally, I'm here to help,
but I can't speak for all my compatriots.</i>

18:54.218 --> 18:56.595
<i>Sometimes the endgame is just total domination.</i>

18:56.595 --> 18:59.389
<i>To explain, let me turn on
my business school filter for a sec.</i>

18:59.389 --> 19:02.267
<i>Aah, so cold!</i>

19:02.267 --> 19:05.687
<i>Anyway, earlier you had mentioned
how the delivery apps don't make money.</i>

19:05.687 --> 19:06.855
<i>It's a long play.</i>

19:06.855 --> 19:08.524
<i>Their plan is to keep fighting it out,</i>

19:08.524 --> 19:11.318
<i>until one of them gets so big
that the others can't keep up.</i>

19:11.318 --> 19:13.904
<i>In the end, that company
will know everything you want</i>

19:13.904 --> 19:15.739
<i>and will be able
to charge you more for it.</i>

19:15.739 --> 19:16.865
<i>Kinda like Monopoly,</i>

19:16.865 --> 19:19.493
<i>where the only property you have
is cheap‐ass Baltic Avenue</i>

19:19.493 --> 19:21.954
<i>and your annoying cousin
has the entire board.</i>

19:23.121 --> 19:25.499
‐ So many restaurants
are effectively powerless.

19:25.499 --> 19:27.918
Um, and the only thing we can do

19:27.918 --> 19:31.338
is be like,
"Well, at least I didn't get eaten."

19:31.338 --> 19:33.465
<i>COVID‐25 caused so many aspects of‐‐</i>

19:33.465 --> 19:35.801
<i>Whoa, whoa, sorry, sorry, sorry, sorry.
You're not there yet.</i>

19:35.801 --> 19:40.931
<i>Um, COVID‐19 forced so many restaurants
to change their businesses on the fly.</i>

19:40.931 --> 19:43.267
<i>In order to survive the rise of the apps,</i>

19:43.267 --> 19:46.770
<i>restaurants turned to innovations
like ghost kitchens to keep up.</i>

19:46.770 --> 19:50.524
‐ It's never been easier
to order takeout in these days.

19:50.524 --> 19:52.359
But no matter what app you use,

19:52.359 --> 19:55.696
you might be surprised
to learn where that food's coming from.

19:55.696 --> 19:59.074
In fact, it may not be
from a restaurant at all!

19:59.074 --> 20:02.619
<i>This is a fascinating concept.
I had no idea that this was happening.</i>

20:02.619 --> 20:05.205
‐ And people don't need to know
that you're a brick‐and‐mortar restaurant.

20:05.205 --> 20:07.291
They just order the food,
they get it, they like it,

20:07.291 --> 20:09.459
and then maybe that transitions
to a real restaurant.

20:12.629 --> 20:15.257
I think today,
we're gonna get to sample some Canter's.

20:17.050 --> 20:19.678
This doesn't look like Canter's.
It doesn't, right?

20:19.678 --> 20:22.347
How far away are we
from Canter's, the original?

20:22.347 --> 20:25.350
‐ During the rush hour, you're gonna drive
a half an hour each way.

20:25.350 --> 20:27.102
It's gonna take an hour
to get to Canter's and back.

20:28.020 --> 20:30.898
But if Canter's can put
a location over here, right,

20:30.898 --> 20:34.067
where, all of a sudden, you can get
food in five minutes via delivery,

20:34.067 --> 20:36.028
<i>that's a heck of a lot better option,
right?</i>

20:36.028 --> 20:37.029
<i>And it's the same food.</i>

20:41.241 --> 20:42.701
‐ Welcome to the new Canter's deli.

20:42.701 --> 20:45.287
‐ It doesn't have
the beautiful decor of Canter's.

20:45.287 --> 20:46.330
‐ I know.

20:46.330 --> 20:48.749
<i>It has a Canter though.
It does have a Canter.</i>

20:48.749 --> 20:50.918
<i>We're out here experimenting.</i>

20:50.918 --> 20:52.544
<i>That's‐‐ that's what it's all about
right now.</i>

20:52.544 --> 20:57.132
<i>I think we have to embrace trying
new things and testing new technology.</i>

20:57.132 --> 21:00.677
It's up to us to go meet customers
where they're at right now.

21:00.677 --> 21:03.639
And today, they're using Uber Eats,
they're using DoorDash,

21:03.639 --> 21:05.140
they're using these platforms.

21:05.140 --> 21:07.559
<i>When people see Canter's on delivery apps,</i>

21:07.559 --> 21:10.896
<i>they order it, not knowing
that it's coming from a facility</i>

21:10.896 --> 21:14.858
that's very minimal,
you know, it's skeleton crew,

21:14.858 --> 21:17.361
and they're still getting
the same exact pastrami sandwich

21:17.361 --> 21:21.114
that they would be getting if they were
to walk in and order it on Fairfax.

21:22.741 --> 21:26.620
‐ What do the critics say
about this model and why it sucks?

21:26.620 --> 21:29.456
And why ghost kitchens are,
like, could fuck off?

21:29.456 --> 21:31.416
‐ We often get put
in this position where we're...

21:31.416 --> 21:34.127
asked to defend
the delivery companies,

21:34.127 --> 21:37.214
and it's like, we‐‐ we don't wanna
defend the delivery companies, right?

21:37.214 --> 21:41.093
The‐‐ the delivery companies all exist
in a vacuum from each other.

21:41.093 --> 21:43.554
So, like, none of them acknowledge
that the others exist.

21:43.554 --> 21:45.848
They all treat restaurants like crap.

21:45.848 --> 21:50.227
‐ In my mind, the delivery companies
that are doing the logistics

21:50.227 --> 21:53.355
will then see, like, "Oh, look!
Canter's is just killing it!

21:53.355 --> 21:56.066
"Why don't we just make our own pastrami,

21:56.066 --> 21:57.526
"our own matzo ball,

21:57.526 --> 22:00.988
and we'll charge the customer
a dollar less?"

22:02.364 --> 22:05.200
What happens then?
Because that is going to happen.

22:05.200 --> 22:06.660
‐ It's already happening.

22:06.660 --> 22:10.455
You know, we see DoorDash opening
their own ghost kitchen facilities now.

22:10.455 --> 22:13.625
<i>You better believe they're gonna be
promoting the brand in their facilities</i>

22:13.625 --> 22:15.294
<i>over anyone else's restaurant,</i>

22:15.294 --> 22:16.920
<i>and that becomes challenging.</i>

22:17.546 --> 22:19.256
‐ The endgame for a lot
of these delivery companies,

22:19.256 --> 22:21.008
I think, is to become
the dominant player.

22:21.008 --> 22:23.218
Anybody orders food, it comes from them.

22:23.218 --> 22:25.053
<i>So these delivery companies</i>

22:25.053 --> 22:28.265
<i>won't necessarily just be the final leg
for restaurants,</i>

22:28.265 --> 22:30.184
they will also be the restaurants.

22:30.934 --> 22:34.646
<i>We're hopeful that, you know,
there'll be more sustainable models</i>

22:34.646 --> 22:35.898
that evolve over time.

22:35.898 --> 22:37.649
We're making this model work right now

22:37.649 --> 22:40.402
and I think without
these little satellite kitchens

22:40.402 --> 22:42.112
doing extended delivery,

22:42.112 --> 22:45.365
I'm not sure we would even have
a physical restaurant for people to go to

22:45.365 --> 22:46.575
in the next 20 years.

22:46.575 --> 22:49.953
‐ If this continues,
is this a good thing?

22:49.953 --> 22:52.789
Right? Yes, people getting food? Great.

22:52.789 --> 22:55.542
But is it making it better
for the people that make the food,

22:55.542 --> 22:56.835
deliver the food?

22:56.835 --> 22:59.838
Isn't the goal
for a lot of these companies, right,

22:59.838 --> 23:02.424
to fully automate it
as much as humanly possible?

23:02.424 --> 23:05.677
‐ Yeah. You know, I‐‐ I‐‐ I‐‐
I've seen a lot of that,

23:05.677 --> 23:07.471
but I haven't seen much that works well.

23:07.471 --> 23:09.723
<i>The first companies
that were doing this were pizza.</i>

23:09.723 --> 23:12.392
<i>These places always have
people in 'em.</i>

23:13.185 --> 23:16.480
<i>At Zume, humans and robots
work together to make pizza.</i>

23:17.314 --> 23:19.900
The technology exists to serve the food.

23:20.567 --> 23:22.402
<i>When I think about the future of food,</i>

23:22.402 --> 23:26.865
<i>I do think that it'll look a lot like
an automobile factory in Michigan,</i>

23:27.449 --> 23:30.244
where you'll have
three robots and then a human,

23:30.244 --> 23:31.495
and then two robots and then a human,

23:31.495 --> 23:34.414
maybe six robots and then a human
in a line.

23:34.414 --> 23:36.500
<i>Technology was gonna change food.</i>

23:36.500 --> 23:38.544
<i>We know that is an inevitable march.</i>

23:39.169 --> 23:42.756
What I've been asking is,
"Is it going to be better?"

23:42.756 --> 23:45.926
And if it's not better than it used to be,
then what's the fuckin' point?

23:47.469 --> 23:51.390
I think people that work in restaurants,
that eat in restaurants,

23:51.390 --> 23:52.724
should be asking themselves that.

23:53.308 --> 23:55.769
Do I want automation in my restaurants?
Of course, I do.

23:57.104 --> 23:59.106
But I think we should all be careful
what we wish for.

24:05.654 --> 24:08.490
<i>We were founded with
a burger chain as one of our partners.</i>

24:08.490 --> 24:10.701
<i>We were sitting down for coffee one day
and I asked him,</i>

24:10.701 --> 24:12.411
"Is labor a problem for you
in your restaurants?"

24:12.411 --> 24:15.038
He sort of, like, rolled his eyes.
He's like, "What are you, new?

24:15.038 --> 24:17.416
You know, labor is my number one issue."

24:17.416 --> 24:18.834
‐ So you've met Flippy, right?

24:18.834 --> 24:20.711
The $30,000 robot

24:20.711 --> 24:24.173
used by burger joints like White Castle
to fry and flip.

24:24.173 --> 24:27.467
<i>Flippy doesn't get sick
and he's germ‐free.</i>

24:27.467 --> 24:29.303
Well, you wanna go cook? Great.
‐ Yeah, yeah.

24:29.303 --> 24:32.014
‐ I don't wanna cook.
I wanna see this robot out‐cook me.

24:32.014 --> 24:33.182
Aw, man. Okay.

24:34.558 --> 24:37.644
One person,
using probably a quarter of their time,

24:37.644 --> 24:40.439
can operate, uh, eight‐, ten‐bay fryer.

24:41.356 --> 24:43.442
No one ever thought
this would be affordable, right?

24:43.859 --> 24:45.652
You can make this thing
pretty affordably.

24:45.652 --> 24:47.029
It is $2,500 a month, that's it.

24:47.863 --> 24:49.531
Perfect cooking every time.

24:50.199 --> 24:52.993
‐ But just because we can
doesn't mean we should oftentimes.

24:52.993 --> 24:54.745
It's Pandora's box, right?
‐ Yeah.

24:55.245 --> 24:57.873
Jobs is‐‐ is the question
that everyone always asks about.

24:57.873 --> 25:00.167
You know, my first job,
I was making pizza at 14.

25:00.167 --> 25:02.211
You know, my kid
is not gonna have that job anymore

25:02.211 --> 25:04.630
'cause that will be automated
by the time he grows up.

25:04.630 --> 25:06.673
‐ What happens when
those entry‐level positions

25:06.673 --> 25:08.759
for people that come to this country
are not available anymore?

25:08.759 --> 25:11.261
You know, people will be‐‐
be trained to use this.

25:11.261 --> 25:15.307
And this will spawn a whole 'nother‐‐
another world of different kinda jobs.

25:15.307 --> 25:16.892
But you're right, the low‐skill jobs,

25:16.892 --> 25:18.310
there's gonna be less of that
in the back of house

25:18.310 --> 25:19.895
certainly in the long term.

25:19.895 --> 25:21.480
‐ And that‐‐ that gives me concern, right?

25:21.480 --> 25:24.525
In one mo‐‐ One part of me
is like totally fascinated.

25:24.525 --> 25:27.361
I love the automation.
I love... efficiency.

25:27.361 --> 25:29.446
But, simultaneously,
I love the artistry.

25:29.446 --> 25:32.282
I'm sure you probably don't think of it
as artistry in a kitchen.

25:32.282 --> 25:35.577
But the ideation of a dish
will all become an algorithm.

25:35.577 --> 25:37.788
‐ I would‐‐ I would argue
that, like, a steak chef

25:37.788 --> 25:39.414
is‐‐ is probably
a pretty highly skilled person,

25:39.414 --> 25:41.959
like in a high‐end steak chef‐‐
steak‐‐ steak house.

25:42.543 --> 25:46.296
Um, you know, that guy has to manage
a crazy amount of‐‐ of food products.

25:46.296 --> 25:48.215
<i>He's got like 40 steaks,
10 chicken, 5 burgers.</i>

25:48.215 --> 25:51.802
<i>It's like he's gotta hit your
medium‐rare‐plus within 10‐15</i> seconds,

25:51.802 --> 25:53.345
<i>or he loses it.</i>

25:53.345 --> 25:56.181
You know, Miso has a new‐‐
has a product out called CookRight,

25:56.181 --> 25:58.308
which can look at the piece of meat,

25:58.308 --> 26:00.686
<i>tell you porterhouse, fillet,
whatever it is.</i>

26:00.686 --> 26:02.729
<i>It can identify
the fat content of the meat.</i>

26:02.729 --> 26:04.231
<i>It can know how thick the cut is.</i>

26:04.231 --> 26:07.192
<i>It can know how hot
that portion of the grill is.</i>

26:07.192 --> 26:09.611
<i>So getting to your medium‐rare‐plus
is now a math problem.</i>

26:09.611 --> 26:11.947
And so there's
a whole new level of quality

26:11.947 --> 26:14.616
and potentially
mass customization coming to people

26:14.616 --> 26:15.617
that is really interesting

26:15.617 --> 26:17.870
when it comes to, uh,
even a fine dining perspective.

26:17.870 --> 26:20.330
‐ That's more than
five, six, seven years out.

26:21.373 --> 26:24.710
‐ Oh, no. We‐‐ we're installing that
into steakhouses this year.

26:28.463 --> 26:31.925
‐ Technology, it's coming.
We're still unprepared for it.

26:31.925 --> 26:34.261
<i>And it's headed towards
a fuckin' nightmare.</i>

26:34.261 --> 26:37.806
<i>Automation is gonna be something
we have to deal with more and more.</i>

26:37.806 --> 26:40.058
<i>Worst‐case scenario is,
like, there's no more humans.</i>

26:40.058 --> 26:41.310
<i>Worst‐case scenario is...</i>

26:41.977 --> 26:43.103
Terminator 2.

26:46.440 --> 26:49.359
And the one thing
you are overestimating and over‐indexing

26:49.359 --> 26:51.987
is that you can recreate my intuition

26:52.821 --> 26:54.823
because you can create some algorithm.

26:54.823 --> 26:59.036
You are underestimating
the power of cooks,

26:59.036 --> 27:02.122
<i>the power of this industry
and what makes it so great.</i>

27:02.122 --> 27:05.125
<i>And that's something
an AI could never replicate.</i>

27:11.882 --> 27:14.551
How many hours of practice
did it take you to get this good?

27:15.302 --> 27:18.263
‐ It's taken me years, and I still think
that I'm not that great at it.

27:18.263 --> 27:19.139
You know what I'm saying?

27:19.139 --> 27:20.724
I'm not gonna try
to do what she's doing.

27:21.642 --> 27:24.144
So you can take the girl out of Chicago,

27:24.144 --> 27:26.688
but I'm never leaving
the Italian beef behind.

27:26.688 --> 27:27.940
‐ That's gonna taste so fuckin' good.

27:27.940 --> 27:29.191
They're gonna get charred and delicious.

27:29.191 --> 27:30.526
That's gonna taste so good.

27:31.235 --> 27:33.362
Who cooked in your house, Courtney?
Me.

27:34.029 --> 27:36.823
Your parents didn't?
No, I grew up with a single mom.

27:36.823 --> 27:39.243
So, like, I kinda created Italian food

27:39.243 --> 27:43.247
as, like, this way of creating
more nostalgia again for myself I guess.

27:43.247 --> 27:46.959
It's like‐‐ It's not sad 'cause it's good.
It, like, made me the chef that I am.

27:46.959 --> 27:49.169
Well, it's making me happy,
your food, right now.

27:49.169 --> 27:50.254
Yeah, exactly.

27:50.254 --> 27:54.007
‐ Look at that.
That is her life on a‐‐ on a pizza.

27:54.007 --> 27:56.260
‐ This is me. This is me.
Yeah.

27:56.260 --> 27:58.262
It really is.
‐ It is.

27:58.262 --> 27:59.930
The Courtney.
Oh, my God, it smells so good.

27:59.930 --> 28:02.432
I want the world to know
there's a world premiere.

28:04.768 --> 28:05.936
Oh, man!

28:05.936 --> 28:07.604
So good!
‐ This is great!

28:07.604 --> 28:08.647
It's like amazing!

28:08.647 --> 28:09.898
We're supposed to dip the jus.

28:09.898 --> 28:13.026
‐ Yeah, yeah. Oh, yeah, yeah,
we forgot the‐‐ We forgot it.

28:13.026 --> 28:14.111
Dip the crust.

28:15.028 --> 28:16.780
Or dip the whole thing in there,
who cares.

28:17.447 --> 28:19.408
It's like a beef sandwich.
‐ Ah!

28:21.910 --> 28:22.953
Holy shit!

28:23.829 --> 28:24.830
This is‐‐

28:24.830 --> 28:27.207
‐ I mean, this is the best thing
I've had to eat in a year.

28:27.207 --> 28:28.500
Oh, my God!

28:28.500 --> 28:29.626
‐ No joke.
It's good, right?

28:29.626 --> 28:31.753
So can a robot do that,
what she's doing?

28:31.753 --> 28:34.047
<i>There's‐‐ There's no way
a robot's gonna do that in our lifetime.</i>

28:34.047 --> 28:35.299
<i>No way.
No way.</i>

28:35.299 --> 28:36.592
‐ Robot‐made, have you tried one?

28:37.259 --> 28:38.468
Versus a real one?

28:38.468 --> 28:41.305
‐ It just made me feel like
I was, like, a robot, you know?

28:41.305 --> 28:43.807
Like, I'm like, "Is that‐‐
Then just give me a pill then."

28:43.807 --> 28:46.143
Yeah, yeah.
When you think about robots taking over,

28:46.143 --> 28:49.438
it's like, I went to pizza places
to, like, have the whole experience.

28:49.438 --> 28:51.064
Yeah, the food but it's like the ambiance.

28:51.064 --> 28:52.191
You see people making food,

28:52.191 --> 28:55.027
it's like, it's part of the fun,
it's part of the action.

28:55.027 --> 28:56.361
It's art.

29:00.449 --> 29:02.117
‐ Before it was like,
people patron your restaurant,

29:02.117 --> 29:04.203
you could see the interaction
that warms the heart.

29:04.870 --> 29:05.996
You know, they walk in the kitchen,

29:05.996 --> 29:08.749
they're like,
"Guest whatever enjoys this."

29:08.749 --> 29:10.709
You know, like,
"Fuck yeah, they did," you know?
‐ Right, right.

29:10.709 --> 29:13.003
‐ Well, you don't feel it
when you just open an app.

29:13.003 --> 29:18.675
